# No Native Browser Dialogs

NEVER use `alert()`, `confirm()`, or `prompt()` in any frontend code. These produce ugly, unbranded OS-level popups that cannot be styled, tracked, or debugged.

## Use the Jungle dialog systems instead

There are two first-party implementations with the same API shape:

- **`jungleDialog`** (`public/js/jungleDialog.js`, on `window`) — toasts for
  alert/success/error, side drawers for confirm/prompt. Used by `admin.js`,
  `jungleAgents.js`, `auth-bootstrap.js`, and any page that loads `jungleDialog.js`.
- **`jungleModal`** (top of `public/js/app.js`, dashboard-local) — centered modal
  dialogs. Used throughout `app.js`.

API (identical for both):

- `await jungleDialog.alert(message, title?)` — informational message, returns `true`
- `await jungleDialog.success(message, title?)` — success styling, returns `true`
- `await jungleDialog.error(message, title?)` — error styling, returns `true`
- `await jungleDialog.confirm(message, title?)` — returns `true` or `false`
- `await jungleDialog.prompt(message, defaultValue?, title?)` — returns `string` or `null`

## Rules

1. All dialog calls are async — use `await` and ensure the enclosing function is `async`
2. Use `.error()` for failure messages, `.success()` for success messages, `.alert()` for informational
3. For confirm patterns: `if (!await jungleDialog.confirm('...')) return;`
4. For prompt patterns: `const val = await jungleDialog.prompt('...'); if (!val) return;`
5. Inside `app.js`, use `jungleModal.*`; everywhere else use `jungleDialog.*`
6. `window.win95Dialog` is a DEPRECATED alias of `jungleDialog` kept one release as a
   safety net — never write new code against it
